# PokeManiac ViewModel Patterns

## Structure Template

Every ViewModel follows this structure:

```kotlin
class MyFeatureViewModel(
    private val repository: MyRepository,
    private val navigator: MyNavigator,
    private val trackingRepository: TrackingRepository
) : ViewModel() {
    
    // ============ UI STATE ============
    @Immutable  // Always annotate — Compose cannot infer stability of sealed classes
    sealed class MyFeatureUiState {
        data object Loading : MyFeatureUiState()
        data class Data(val items: PersistentList<ItemUI>) : MyFeatureUiState()
        data object EmptyResult : MyFeatureUiState()
    }
    
    private val _uiState: MutableStateFlow<MyFeatureUiState> = MutableStateFlow(Loading)
    val uiState: StateFlow<MyFeatureUiState> = _uiState.asStateFlow()
    
    // ============ EVENTS / ERRORS ============
    private val _error = MutableSharedFlow<UiError>()
    val error = _error.asSharedFlow()
    
    // ============ PUBLIC ACTIONS ============
    fun start() {
        viewModelScope.launch {
            // Load initial data
        }
    }
    
    // ============ PRIVATE IMPLEMENTATION ============
    private suspend fun loadData() {
        try {
            _uiState.update { Loading }
            val items = repository.fetchItems()
            _uiState.update { MyFeatureUiState.Data(items.toPersistentList()) }
        } catch (e: CancellationException) {
            throw e
        } catch (e: Exception) {
            _error.emit(UiError.from(e))
            _uiState.update { MyFeatureUiState.EmptyResult }
        }
    }
}
```

---

## State Management Rules

### ✅ Use Sealed Classes for UI State — Always Annotate @Immutable

Always represent UI state as a sealed class with specific cases, and always annotate with `@Immutable`. Without it, the Compose compiler treats sealed classes as **unstable** and recomposes defensively even when the state hasn't changed.

```kotlin
import androidx.compose.runtime.Immutable

@Immutable  // Required — Compose cannot infer stability of sealed classes
sealed class UiState {
    data object Loading : UiState()
    data class Data(val items: PersistentList<ItemUI>) : UiState()
    data object EmptyResult : UiState()
}
```

### ✅ Annotate UI Models with @Immutable or @Stable

UI model data classes passed to Composables must be annotated so the Compose compiler can skip recomposition when they haven't changed.

```kotlin
import androidx.compose.runtime.Immutable
import androidx.compose.runtime.Stable

// @Immutable — all fields are stable (String, Int, enum, PersistentList)
@Immutable
data class ItemUI(
    val id: String,
    val name: String,
    val count: Int
)

// @Stable — when a field type has correct equals() but is not @Immutable (e.g. Uri)
@Stable
data class CardUI(
    val id: String,
    val imageUri: Uri  // Uri: behaviorally immutable, not annotated by framework
)
```

### ✅ Use PersistentList for Immutable Collections
```kotlin
import kotlinx.collections.immutable.PersistentList
import kotlinx.collections.immutable.toPersistentList

// All collection fields in UI models and UiState must use PersistentList.
// Plain List<T> is treated as unstable by Compose (MutableList implements it).
data class Data(val items: PersistentList<ItemUI>) : UiState()
```

### ✅ Typed Error Flow — Use `UiError`

Always use `UiError` (from `coreui`) instead of raw `Exception`. This guarantees a non-null, user-facing message and prevents `"null"` showing in snackbars.

```kotlin
import com.shodo.android.coreui.UiError

private val _error = MutableSharedFlow<UiError>()
val error = _error.asSharedFlow()

// In catch blocks:
catch (e: Exception) {
    _error.emit(UiError.from(e))
}
```

`UiError.from(e)` returns `UiError(message = e.message ?: "Something went wrong")`.

Screen collects errors in `observeWithLifecycle` for snackbars:
```kotlin
viewModel.error.observeWithLifecycle(lifecycleOwner) { error ->
    snackbarHostState.showSnackbar(error.message)  // Never .toString()
}
```

### ❌ Don't use Boolean flags
```kotlin
// BAD
var isLoading: Boolean = false
var hasError: Boolean = false

// GOOD
sealed class UiState {
    data object Loading : UiState()
    data object Error : UiState()
    data class Data(val items: List<Item>) : UiState()
}
```

